'''Kawahla''' is an ethnic group of Eastern [[Sudan]].<ref>{{cite book |last= |first=H. R. J. |date=1986 |title=Rural Development in White Nile Province, Sudan: A Study of Interaction Between Man and Natural Resources, Issue 59 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4tQDAQAAIAAJ&q=Kawahla+people+Sudan&dq=Kawahla+people+Sudan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBWoVChMIguK1oKvpxwIVh1uSCh3vVAiV |publisher=[[United Nations University]] |page=66 |isbn=9280805797 |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Johnson |first1=David Hamilton |last2=Anderson |first2=David M. |date=2011 |title=The Ecology of Survival: Case Studies from Northeast African History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5yb7dLGdVdMC&pg=PA158&dq=Kawahla+people+Sudan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CFEQ6AEwCWoVChMIguK1oKvpxwIVh1uSCh3vVAiV#v=onepage&q=Kawahla%20people%20Sudan&f=false |publisher=[[I.B. Tauris]] |page=158 |isbn=1870915003 |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Kramer |first1=Robert S. |last2=Lobban Jr. |first2=Richard A. |last3=Fluehr-Lobban |first3=Carolyn |date=2013 |title=Historical Dictionary of the Sudan |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0OKZRewiEOsC&pg=PA148&dq=Kawahla+people+Sudan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDYQ6AEwBDgUahUKEwjx5J2ysunHAhVOCZIKHc-jAvQ#v=onepage&q=Kawahla%20people%20Sudan&f=false |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield|Scarecrow Press]] |page=148-331 |isbn=0810879409 |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> They are an Arabic ethnic group. They speak [[Sudanese Arabic]] and members of this ethnicity are [[Muslim]]s. The Kawahla are known to be the descents from [[Banu Assad]] tribe who migrated from the [[Hijaz]] to Sudan.<ref>{{cite book |last=MacMichael |first=Harold Alfred |date=1922 |title=A History of the Arabs in the Sudan and Some Account of the People who Preceded Them and of the Tribes Inhabiting Dárfūr, Volume 2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LtIDAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA148&dq=Kawahla+people+Sudan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAGoVChMIguK1oKvpxwIVh1uSCh3vVAiV#v=onepage&q=Kawahla%20people%20Sudan&f=false |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |page=194 |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> and has over 90 segments of the tribe. It is also the biggest tribe in Sudan.
Most of the Kawahla are farmers, and the main crops they grow are [[sorghum]], [[wheat]], [[cotton]], beans (luba) and other fruits such as La loba and Nabag. Studies of the Kawahla in [[Kurdufan]] found that they migrate from the wet season pasture to grazing land near permanent wells to wait for the dry season.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jousse |first1=Hélène |last2=Lesur |first2=Joséphine |date=2011 |title=People and Animals in Holocene Africa: Recent Advances in Archaeozoology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xjl0a50AWIwC&pg=PA105&dq=Kawahla+people+Sudan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBmoVChMIguK1oKvpxwIVh1uSCh3vVAiV#v=onepage&q=Kawahla%20people%20Sudan&f=false |publisher=Africa Magna Verlag |page=105 |isbn=3937248277 |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> In the 19th century, [[Hedley Vicars]] encountered the Kawahla and, when they asked him to settle their dispute with other tribes, he ruled over them.<ref>{{cite book |last=Manger |first=Leif O. |date=1994 |title=From the Mountains to the Plains: The Integration of the Lafofa Nuba Into Sudanese Society |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ms3N4_4Swb0C&pg=PA44&dq=Kawahla+people+Sudan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAmoVChMIguK1oKvpxwIVh1uSCh3vVAiV#v=onepage&q=Kawahla%20people%20Sudan&f=false |publisher=[[Nordic Africa Institute]] |page=44 |isbn=9171063366 |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> [[Lord Edward Gleichen]] also wrote about the Kawahla.<ref>{{cite book |date=1905 |title=The Anglo-Egyptian Sudan, Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a3UPAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA119&dq=Kawahla+people+Sudan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CD0Q6AEwBTgKahUKEwighIfWsOnHAhVMDpIKHbapDSU#v=onepage&q=Kawahla%20people%20Sudan&f=false |location=Sudan |publisher=H. M. Stationery Office |page=109-325 |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Gleichen |first=Edward |date=1905 |title=The Anglo-Egyptian Sudan: A Compendium Prepared by Officers of the Sudan Government, Volume 2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3bk2AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA164&dq=Kawahla+people+Sudan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDgQ6AEwBDgKahUKEwighIfWsOnHAhVMDpIKHbapDSU#v=onepage&q=Kawahla%20people%20Sudan&f=false |location=Sudan |publisher=H. M. Stationery Office |page=67-164 |isbn= |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>
