[[Image:tubeteika.JPG|thumb|A [[Kazakhs|Kazakh]] tubeteika|right]] A '''tubeteika''' ({{lang-ru|тюбете́йка}}) is a [[Russian language|Russian]] word for many varieties of traditional [[Central Asia]]n [[cap]]s. Tubeteikas are today worn in [[Tajikistan]], [[Kazakhstan]], [[Kyrgyzstan]], and [[Uzbekistan]], as well as in Muslim-populated regions of [[Russia]] (mainly [[Tatars]]) and [[Azerbaijan]]. The skullcap worn by Uzbeks and Uyghurs is called a [[doppa]] and has a square base.
Tubeteikas are worn typically by the [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] ethnic groups of the region. It bears some superficial resemblance to the [[yurt]], another Central Asian cultural icon.
The ''-ka'' at the end is a Russian [[diminutive suffix]], as with ''[[wikt:shapka|shapka]]'', ''[[ushanka]]'' and ''[[budenovka]]''. In [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]], it is called ''tahiya'' ("[[Taqiyah_(cap)|taqiyah]]").
== Doppa == {{main|Doppa|Taqiyah (cap)}} The Uzbek ''doppa'' or ''duppi'' ({{lang-uz|doʻppi}}) is considered an [[applied art]] form and an important part of the traditional folk costume.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sairamtour.com/news/gems/37.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928121813/http://www.sairamtour.com/news/gems/37.html|dead-url=yes|archive-date=28 September 2007|title=Tubeteika suits everybody|accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> Black with a flat, square base,<ref name="MentgesShamukhitdinova2013">{{cite book|last1=Mentges|first1=Gabriele|last2=Shamukhitdinova|first2=Lola|title=Modernity of Tradition: Uzbek Textile Culture Today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aUy-AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA115|year=2013|publisher=Waxmann Verlag|isbn=978-3-8309-7906-7|page=115}}</ref> In [[Chust, Uzbekistan]], the caps are made with white embroidery with "four arches [which] represent impenetrable gates that will keep all enemies at bay; the burning peppers protect against the evil eye; and the almonds or ''bodom'' are said to symbolise life and fertility".<ref name="Lovell-Hoare2013">{{cite book|last1=Lovell-Hoare|first1=Sophie|last2=Lovell-Hoare|first2=Max|title=Uzbekistan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qF6PJda90gYC&pg=PA117|date=8 July 2013|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-84162-461-7|page=117}}</ref>
Also, there is a trend among [[Sephardic]] and [[Moroccan Jews]] to wear Uzbeki tubeteikas as a [[kippah]].
